        <p>Imagine that the purpose of these tables is to take an input somewhere in the left column, and then look up an output from the right column. For example, in the first table, when the input is <q>black</q>, the output would <q>white</q>. The first table's function is to provide a word with opposite meaning of the input word. This is not a numerical example.</p>

        <p>The third table <em>does</em> consist  of numbers.  And its function is to take a number as input, and give twice of that number as output. A pithy way to describe the pattern is <q><m>y=2x\text{,}</m></q> where we are using <m>x</m> to represent the input, and <m>y</m> to represent the output. Let's make the third table more mathematical:</p>

