    <exercise xml:id="exercise-linear-data"> 
        <webwork>
            <pg-macros>
                <macro-file>parserAssignment.pl</macro-file>
            </pg-macros>
            <setup>
                <var name="$x[0]"><static>0</static></var>
                <var name="$x[1]"><static>1</static></var>
                <var name="$x[2]"><static>2</static></var>
                <var name="$x[3]"><static>3</static></var>
                <var name="$y[0]"><static>-1</static></var>
                <var name="$y[1]"><static>2</static></var>
                <var name="$y[2]"><static>5</static></var>
                <var name="$y[3]"><static>8</static></var>
                <var name="$eq"><static>y=3x-1</static></var>
                <pg-code>
                    @x=(0..3);
                    $f=Formula("-1+3x");
                    @y=map{$f->eval(x=>$_)}@x;
                    Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                    parser::Assignment->Allow;
                    $eq=Formula("y=$f")->reduce;
                </pg-code>
            </setup>
            <statement>
                <table>
                    <tabular >
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[0]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[0]" /></m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[1]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[1]" /></m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[2]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[2]" /></m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[3]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[3]" /></m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>Write an equation in the form <m>y=\ldots</m> suggested by the data in the table.</p>
                <p><var name="$eq" width="20" /></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The pattern here is not immediately apparent. But here is an approach many people use: consider what is happening from one row to the next. With these <m>x</m>-values, each goes up by the same amount, <m>1</m>, from one row to the next. Meanwhile the <m>y</m>-values are <em>also</em> increasing by the same amount with each row, by <m>3</m> each row.</p>
                <table>
                    <tabular >
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell />
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                            <cell />
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell />
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[0]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[0]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell />
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[1]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[1]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}+3</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[2]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[2]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}+3</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[3]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[3]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}+3</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <p>This tells us that the <term>rate of change</term> from one data point to the next is always the same: <m>3</m> units of <m>y</m> for every <m>1</m> unit of <m>x</m>.</p>

                <p>We know what the output from <m>0</m> is: it's <m>-1</m>. And our observation about the constant rate of change tells us that if we moved <m>x</m> units forward from <m>0</m> to <m>x</m>, the ouput would increase by <m>\overbrace{3+3+\cdots+3}^{x\text{ times}}</m>, which is <m>3x</m>. So the output would be <m>-1+3x</m>.</p>

                <p>So the equation is <m><var name="$eq" /></m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </webwork>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise> 
        <webwork>
            <pg-macros>
