            </pg-macros>
            <setup>
                <var name="$x[0]"><static>0</static></var>
                <var name="$x[1]"><static>1</static></var>
                <var name="$x[2]"><static>2</static></var>
                <var name="$x[3]"><static>3</static></var>
                <var name="$y[0]"><static>0</static></var>
                <var name="$y[1]"><static>1</static></var>
                <var name="$y[2]"><static>4</static></var>
                <var name="$y[3]"><static>9</static></var>
                <var name="$eq"><static>y=x^2</static></var>
                <pg-code>
                    @x=(0..3);
                    $f=Formula("x^2");
                    @y=map{$f->eval(x=>$_)}@x;
                    Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                    parser::Assignment->Allow;
                    $eq=Formula("y=$f");
                </pg-code>
            </setup>
            <statement>
                <table>
                    <tabular >
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[0]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[0]" /></m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[1]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[1]" /></m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[2]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[2]" /></m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[3]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[3]" /></m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>Write an equation in the form <m>y=\ldots</m> suggested by the data in the table.</p>
                <p><var name="$eq" width="20" /></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We might try the approach we just used in the previous exercise.</p>
                <table>
                    <tabular >
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell />
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                            <cell />
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell />
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[0]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[0]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell />
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[1]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[1]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}+1</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[2]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[2]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}+3</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$x[3]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m><var name="$y[3]" /></m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}+5</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>This time the rate of change is not constant from one row to the next. Even though <m>x</m>-values are increasing by the same amount, <m>1</m>, with each row, the <m>y</m>-values are increasing by larger and larger amounts.</p> 
                <p>Fortunately, if we stare a little more at the numbers, we can see a simpler pattern: each <m>y</m>-value is the square of the corresponding <m>x</m>-value. So the equation is <m><var name="$eq" /></m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </webwork>
    </exercise> 
