            <p>What is the <term>rate of change</term> in Oregon invasive cancer diagnoses between 2000 and 2010? The actual change in diagnoses is <me>19727-17446=2281</me> and <m>10</m> years passed in between (which you can calculate as <m>2010-2000</m>). So the rate of change is <m>2281</m> diagnoses per <m>10</m> years, or: <me>\frac{2281\,\text{diagnoses}}{10\,\text{year}}=228.1\,\frac{\text{diagnoses}}{\text{year}}\text{.}</me></p> 
        </example>

        <p>Now you try:</p>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-cancer-data">
            <webwork>
                <setup>
                    <pg-code>
                        @x=(1999..2013);
                        @y=(17599,17446,17847,17887,17559,18499,18682,19112,19376,20370,19909,19727,20636,20035,20458);
                        %f=map{$x[$_]=>$y[$_]}(0..14); 
                        $r[0]=($f{2002}-$f{1999})/(2002-1999);
                        $r[1]=($f{2011}-$f{2003})/(2011-2003);
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>Use the data in <xref ref="example-cancer-data">Example</xref> to find the rate of change in Oregon invasive cancer diagnoses between 1999 and 2002. Just give the numerical value; the units are provided.</p>
                    <p><var name="$r[0]" width="10" /><m>\,\frac{\text{diagnoses}}{\text{year}}</m></p>
                    <p>And what was the rate of change between 2003 and 2011?</p>
                    <p><var name="$r[1]" width="10" /><m>\,\frac{\text{diagnoses}}{\text{year}}</m></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>To find the rate of chage between 1999 and 2002, calculate <me>\frac{17887-17599}{2002-1999}=96\text{.}</me></p>
                    <p>To find the rate of chage between 2003 and 2011, calculate <me>\frac{20636-17559}{2011-2003}=384.625\text{.}</me></p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>

        <p>We are ready to give a formal defintion for <term>rate of change</term>. Considering the pattern from <xref ref="example-cancer-data">Example</xref> and <xref ref="exercise-cancer-data">Exercise</xref>, we settle on:</p> 

    
        <definition>
            <title>Rate of Change</title>
            <statement>
                <p>If <m>\left(x_1,y_1\right)</m> and <m>\left(x_2,y_2\right)</m> are two data points from a set of two-variable data, then the <term>rate of change</term> between them is <me>\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}\text{.}</me></p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
    
        <p>In <xref ref="example-cancer-data">Example</xref> and <xref ref="exercise-cancer-data">Exercise</xref> we found three rates of change. <xref ref="figure-cancer-data">Figure</xref> highlihgts the three pairs of points that were used to make these calculations.</p>
    
        <figure xml:id="figure-cancer-data">
            <caption />
            <image width="50%">
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xlabel={year},
                            ylabel={count},
                            ytick=,
                            xmin=1995,xmax=2016,
                            ymin=15000,ymax=21000,
