            </image>
        </figure>
    
        <p>Note how the larger the rate of change between two points (<m>96\lt228.1\lt384.6</m>), the steeper the line is that connects them.</p>
    
        <p>In the solution to <xref ref="exercise-linear-data">Exercise</xref>, the key observation was that each time <m>x</m> increased by <m>1\text{,}</m> then <m>y</m> increased by <m>3</m>. The <term>rate of change</term> from one row to the next was constant: <m>3</m> units of increase in <m>y</m> for every <m>1</m> unit of increase in <m>x</m>. This would mean that if we plotted the data from that exercise, all of the lines connecting a pair of data points would all have the same steepness. You can see this in <xref ref="figure-linear-data">Figure</xref>.</p>
    
        <figure xml:id="figure-linear-data">
            <caption />
            <image width="50%">
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-5,ymax=9,ytick={-4,2,...,8},minor ytick={-5,-4,...,9},]
                        \addplot[only marks]coordinates{
                               (0,-1)
                               (1,2)
                               (2,5)
                               (3,8)
                        };
                        \addplot[primarycurve,-] coordinates {(0,-1) (3,8)};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
    
        <p>So if the rate of change is the same between any two points in a data set, then you can conclude the graph will be a straight line even without making the graph. We call this kind of relationship a <term>linear</term> relationship. More details about linear relationships will be discussed in later sections. Right now in this section, we feel it is important to simply be able to identify if data has a linear relationship or not.</p>

        <exercise>
            <webwork>
                <setup>
                    <var name="$x[0]"><static>-8</static></var>
                    <var name="$x[1]"><static>-5</static></var>
                    <var name="$x[2]"><static>-2</static></var>
                    <var name="$x[3]"><static>1</static></var>
                    <var name="$y[0]"><static>3.1</static></var>
